                <h2>Introduction</h2>
<blockquote>
<p>"In the field of overseas advertising, the refinement level of account structure directly determines the ceiling of campaign efficiency." — This is the consensus among every senior media buyer.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>When we examine advertising accounts with low efficiency and persistently poor ROI, we often find a common problem: <strong>chaotic account structure, unclear hierarchical relationships, and confused attribution logic</strong>. On the contrary, top overseas companies' advertising accounts often exhibit highly organized and refined structural characteristics, where each level has clear responsibilities and optimization logic.</p>
<p>This article will deeply explore how to systematically improve campaign efficiency through refined account structure, covering everything from macro-level account planning to micro-level creative management, helping you build a scientific and reusable advertising architecture system.</p>
<h2>Part 1: Core Value of Refined Account Structure</h2>
<h3>1.1 Why Account Structure Matters So Much</h3>
<p>In digital advertising, <strong>Account Structure</strong> refers to the organizational methods and logical relationships of various hierarchical elements within an advertising account. It determines how ads reach target audiences, how budgets are allocated, and how data is attributed.</p>
<p>An excellent account structure brings the following core values:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Precise Audience Targeting</strong>: Through proper Ad Set division, ensure each group of ads targets only a single audience characteristic, avoiding overlap and resource waste</li>
<li><strong>Scientific Budget Control</strong>: Ads for different products, regions, and objectives can independently control budgets, achieving optimal resource allocation</li>
<li><strong>Clear Attribution Analysis</strong>: A clear structure makes data traceable at all levels, facilitating accurate evaluation of campaign performance</li>
<li><strong>Efficient Optimization Iteration</strong>: Problem identification is more precise, and optimization decisions are more evidence-based</li>
</ul>
<h3>1.2 The Cost of Chaotic Account Structure</h3>
<p>According to industry research data, <strong>over 60% of campaign efficiency losses stem from improper account structure design</strong>. Common chaotic structures lead to:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Budget Waste</strong>: Multiple Ad Sets competing for the same audience group, causing internal bidding to drive up costs</li>
<li><strong>Data Distortion</strong>: Different dimensions mixed together, making it impossible to accurately determine which variables caused performance differences</li>
<li><strong>Difficult Optimization</strong>: When performance fluctuates, it's hard to quickly identify whether it's an audience issue, creative issue, or bidding issue</li>
<li><strong>Poor Scalability</strong>: Business growth makes accounts difficult to scale, and systematic reconstruction costs are high</li>
</ul>
<h2>Part 2: Mainstream Platform Account Architecture Analysis</h2>
<h3>2.1 Meta Ads Account Architecture</h3>
<p>Meta (Facebook/Instagram) uses the classic <strong>three-level structure</strong>:</p>
<pre><code>Ad Account
    ├── Campaign
    │   ├── Ad Set
    │   │   └── Ad
    │   └── Ad Set
    │       └── Ad
    └── Campaign
        └── ...
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Core Responsibilities of Each Level</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Campaign Level</strong>: Defines marketing objectives (brand awareness, traffic, conversion, app install, etc.), sets overall budget and payment methods</li>
<li><strong>Ad Set Level</strong>: Defines audience targeting, placements, scheduling, bidding strategies, and budget allocation</li>
<li><strong>Ad Level</strong>: Defines specific ad creative, copy, and CTA (Call to Action)</li>
</ul>
<h3>2.2 Google Ads Account Architecture</h3>
<p>Google Ads uses a <strong>multi-level structure</strong> that is more flexible but also more complex:</p>
<pre><code>Account
    └── Search Campaign
        ├── Ad Group
        │   └── Keywords + Ad Copy
        └── Ad Group
            └── Keywords + Ad Copy
    └── Display Campaign
        └── ...
</code></pre>
<h3>2.3 TikTok Ads Account Architecture</h3>
<p>TikTok's account structure is similar to Meta's but adjusted for short video platform characteristics:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Campaign Level</strong>: Sets ad types (branded, performance) and budget</li>
<li><strong>Ad Group Level</strong>: Defines audience, video cutdown settings, placements</li>
<li><strong>Ad Level</strong>: Uploads creative materials, sets CTA copy</li>
</ul>
<h2>Part 3: Design Principles for Refined Account Structure</h2>
<h3>3.1 Single Variable Principle</h3>
<p><strong>The core principle of refined account structure is the "Single Variable Principle"</strong>: adjustments at each level should only affect one dimension of change, while other variables remain constant.</p>
<p><strong>Practical Case</strong>:</p>
<p>A cross-border e-commerce client promoting home products in European and American markets initially structured their account like this:</p>
<pre><code>Campaign: Home Products Promotion
├── Ad Set: EU/US + 25-45 + Parents + Conversion
├── Ad Set: EU/US + 25-45 + Non-parents + Conversion
├── Ad Set: EU/US + 45-60 + Parents + Conversion
└── Ad Set: EU/US + 45-60 + Non-parents + Conversion
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Problems with this structure</strong>: Different Ad Sets had <strong>audience overlap</strong>, and both age and family status variables changed simultaneously, making it impossible to determine which factor had the greater impact on performance.</p>
<p><strong>Optimized Structure</strong>:</p>
<pre><code>Campaign: Home Products - Age Test
├── Ad Set: EU/US + 25-45 + All Family Status + Conversion
└── Ad Set: EU/US + 45-60 + All Family Status + Conversion

Campaign: Home Products - Family Status Test
├── Ad Set: EU/US + Parents + All Ages + Conversion
└── Ad Set: EU/US + Non-parents + All Ages + Conversion
</code></pre>
<p>Through split testing, the client discovered that <strong>age factor impact was 3 times greater than family status</strong>, allowing them to concentrate budgets on the 25-45 age group and increase ROI by 42%.</p>
<h3>3.2 Structured Scalability Principle</h3>
<p><strong>Account structure needs to support business expansion</strong>, and scalability should be considered from the initial design phase.</p>
<p><strong>Recommended Structured Naming System</strong>:</p>
<pre><code>[Product Line]_[Target Market]_[Audience Type]_[Creative Format]_[Test Label]

Examples:
Shoes_EU_Women25-35_Lifestyle_A/B_Test
Electronics_US_Gaming-Interest_Video_Control
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Advantages of This Naming Approach</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Immediately identify ad ownership and attributes</li>
<li>Easy data filtering and analysis</li>
<li>New ads can be quickly positioned in the correct location</li>
</ul>
<h3>3.3 Budget Isolation Principle</h3>
<p><strong>Different marketing objectives, product lines, and testing phases should use independent budget pools</strong> to avoid mutual influence.</p>
<p><strong>Practical Recommendations</strong>:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Budget Type</th>
<th>Recommended Ratio</th>
<th>Management Strategy</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Main Scaling Campaigns</td>
<td>60-70%</td>
<td>Stable delivery, moderate scaling</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Potential Testing Campaigns</td>
<td>15-20%</td>
<td>Active testing, rapid iteration</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>New Product/Market Testing</td>
<td>10-15%</td>
<td>Cautious exploration, controlled risk</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Brand Building Campaigns</td>
<td>5-10%</td>
<td>Long-term investment, monitor awareness metrics</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h2>Part 4: Campaign Level Refinement Strategies</h2>
<h3>4.1 Split Campaigns by Marketing Objective</h3>
<p><strong>Different marketing objectives should use independent Campaigns</strong> for the following reasons:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>More Precise Budget Control</strong>: Each objective can independently set budget caps, preventing one objective from crowding out others</li>
<li><strong>More Matching Bidding Strategies</strong>: Conversion-focused goals require completely different bidding strategies than brand awareness goals</li>
<li><strong>Clearer Data Attribution</strong>: Each Campaign's CPA and ROAS can be calculated independently</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Case Analysis</strong>:</p>
<p>An overseas App pursuing both brand awareness and app installs during its promotion period initially used different Ad Sets within the same Campaign:</p>
<pre><code>Campaign: App Promotion
├── Ad Set: Brand Awareness + Fixed Bid $2 CPM
├── Ad Set: App Install + Target CPA $1.5
└── Ad Set: App Install + Target CPA $2
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Problems</strong>: The two objectives mixed together made it difficult for the system to optimize, and ROI fluctuated significantly.</p>
<p><strong>After Optimization</strong>:</p>
<pre><code>Campaign: App Promotion - Brand Awareness
├── Ad Set: Brand Awareness + Fixed Bid $2 CPM

Campaign: App Promotion - Install Volume
├── Ad Set: Install Target + Target CPA $1.5
└── Ad Set: Install Testing + Target CPA $2
</code></pre>
<p>After splitting, the brand Campaign's CPM cost decreased by 18%, and the install Campaign's CPA stability improved by 35%.</p>
<h3>4.2 Split Campaigns by Product/Service Line</h3>
<p><strong>Companies with multiple product lines or brands should split Campaigns by product line</strong>:</p>
<pre><code>Campaign: Skincare Line - Anti-Aging Series
Campaign: Skincare Line - Hydration Series
Campaign: Skincare Line - Sunscreen Series
Campaign: Makeup Line - Foundation Series
Campaign: Makeup Line - Lip Series
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Advantages</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Each product line's budget is independently controllable</li>
<li>Easy to track each product line's LTV and ROI</li>
<li>Supports differentiated audience strategies</li>
</ul>
<h2>Part 5: Ad Set Level Refinement Strategies</h2>
<h3>5.1 Scientific Methods for Audience Grouping</h3>
<p><strong>The core task of Ad Set level is to split audiences by one dimension for testing</strong>. Common grouping dimensions include:</p>
<h4>5.1.1 Demographic Dimensions</h4>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Dimension</th>
<th>Applicable Scenarios</th>
<th>Considerations</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Age</td>
<td>Products with clearly varying audience needs by age</td>
<td>Avoid overly granular age segments (minimum sample size needed ≥1000/day per group)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Gender</td>
<td>Products with significant gender differences</td>
<td>Some platforms support custom gender combinations</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Income Level</td>
<td>High ticket size or luxury products</td>
<td>Data accuracy varies by region</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Family Status</td>
<td>Household consumer products</td>
<td>Combined with age may create more variables</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h4>5.1.2 Interest &amp; Behavior Dimensions</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Interests</strong>: Express long-term interest in certain content categories, suitable for brand awareness stage</li>
<li><strong>Behaviors</strong>: Based on actual behavioral data, suitable for performance conversion stage</li>
<li><strong>Custom Audiences</strong>: Existing customers or engaged users, higher conversion rates</li>
<li><strong>Lookalike Audiences</strong>: New users expanded from seed users, balancing quality and scale</li>
</ul>
<h4>5.1.3 Geographic Dimensions</h4>
<p><strong>Scenarios for splitting Ad Sets by geography</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Different markets have different regulatory restrictions (e.g., GDPR, CCPA)</li>
<li>Pricing strategies vary by region</li>
<li>Logistics or service coverage is limited</li>
</ul>
<h3>5.2 Refined Management of Placements</h3>
<p><strong>User behavior characteristics vary greatly across different placements</strong>, requiring independent management:</p>
<p>Using Meta as an example:</p>
<pre><code>Campaign: Product Promotion
├── Ad Set: Feed (Facebook Feed + Instagram Feed)
│   └── Audience: 25-45 + Lifestyle interests
├── Ad Set: Stories (Instagram Stories + Messenger Stories)
│   └── Audience: 25-35 + Young lifestyle
├── Ad Set: Reels (Instagram Reels)
│   └── Audience: 18-30 + Entertainment interests
└── Ad Set: Audience Network
    └── Audience: Broad coverage + Lower bids
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Optimization Focus for Each Placement</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Feed</strong>: Suitable for in-depth content, emphasizing value proposition; CTR relatively lower but conversion rate higher</li>
<li><strong>Stories</strong>: Requires full-screen vertical creative, emphasizing visual impact; suitable for fast-paced, younger users</li>
<li><strong>Reels</strong>: Short video-focused, emphasizing entertainment and viral potential</li>
<li><strong>Search Ads</strong>: Precise keyword targeting, copy needs to include search intent</li>
</ul>
<h3>5.3 Selection of Bidding Strategies</h3>
<p><strong>Choose appropriate bidding strategies based on marketing objectives and optimization stages</strong>:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Bidding Strategy</th>
<th>Applicable Goals</th>
<th>Pros &amp; Cons Analysis</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Lowest Cost</td>
<td>Maximize conversion volume</td>
<td>Costs may fluctuate, but optimal long-term</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Cost Cap</td>
<td>Stable CPA</td>
<td>Costs controlled, but volume may be limited</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Highest Value</td>
<td>Maximize LTV</td>
<td>Suitable for e-commerce with multiple SKUs</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Manual Bidding</td>
<td>Testing stage</td>
<td>Complete control, but requires more effort</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h2>Part 6: Ad Level Refinement Strategies</h2>
<h3>6.1 A/B Testing for Creative Materials</h3>
<p><strong>Each Ad Set should test at least 3-5 different ad creatives</strong>, but note:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Change only one variable at a time</strong>: such as only changing images, only changing copy, or only changing CTA</li>
<li><strong>Sample size must be sufficient</strong>: Each creative needs at least 100-200 conversion events to draw conclusions</li>
<li><strong>Reasonable testing period</strong>: Run for at least 7 days to avoid accidental fluctuations</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Creative Testing Matrix Example</strong>:</p>
<pre><code>Ad Set: Women 25-35 - Anti-Aging Products
├── Ad 1: Before/After comparison + Emphasize quick results
├── Ad 2: User testimonial screenshot + Emphasize word-of-mouth
├── Ad 3: Ingredient analysis graphic + Emphasize safety
├── Ad 4: Video (30 seconds) + Emphasize usage scenarios
└── Ad 5: Carousel + Multiple product showcase
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Data Analysis Dimensions</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>CTR (Click-Through Rate): Reflects material attractiveness</li>
<li>CVR (Conversion Rate): Reflects landing page or product attractiveness</li>
<li>CPA (Cost Per Acquisition): Comprehensive performance indicator</li>
<li>Frequency: Avoid user fatigue</li>
</ul>
<h3>6.2 Consistency Between Ad and Landing Page</h3>
<p><strong>Consistency between ad creative and landing page directly impacts conversion rates</strong>, which also needs consideration at the ad level:</p>
<p><strong>Case</strong>: An independent site promoting summer dresses</p>
<p><strong>Low Consistency Approach</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Ad Creative: Fashion model street style photo</li>
<li>Landing Page: Comprehensive product listing page, users need to find it themselves</li>
<li>Problem: Large gap between user expectations and actual experience, high page bounce rate</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>High Consistency Approach</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Ad Creative: Same model wearing the same dress + "Buy Now" button</li>
<li>Landing Page: Directly display the dress detail page, including model photos, size selection, quick buy button</li>
<li>Effect: Conversion rate improved by approximately 35%</li>
</ul>
<h3>6.3 Application of Dynamic Product Ads (DPA)</h3>
<p><strong>For e-commerce clients, Dynamic Product Ads (DPA) are a powerful tool for improving efficiency</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>System automatically displays the most relevant products based on user behavior</li>
<li>Suitable for independent sites with many SKUs and frequent updates</li>
<li>Can set rules: prioritize popular products, weight higher-margin products, etc.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Part 7: Practical Process for Refined Account Structure</h2>
<h3>7.1 Account Audit and Diagnosis</h3>
<p><strong>Before restructuring the account, a comprehensive account audit is needed</strong>:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Historical Data Analysis</strong>: Identify high and low-performing Campaigns from the past 3-6 months</li>
<li><strong>Structural Problem Identification</strong>: List existing structural issues</li>
<li><strong>Data Attribution Verification</strong>: Confirm whether attribution logic at each level is correct</li>
<li><strong>Resource and Constraint Assessment</strong>: Understand budget, personnel, and platform limitations</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Account Audit Checklist</strong>:</p>
<pre><code>□ Are Campaign names standardized and clear?
□ Are each Campaign's marketing objectives single?
□ Is there audience overlap between Ad Sets?
□ Does audience segmentation meet testing needs?
□ Do bidding strategies match marketing objectives?
□ Are ad creatives classified by variables for testing?
□ Is data tracking complete (Pixel, SDK)?
□ Is budget allocation at each level reasonable?
</code></pre>
<h3>7.2 New Architecture Design and Testing</h3>
<p><strong>Implement the new architecture in phases</strong>:</p>
<p><strong>Phase 1: Create New Test Account</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Build Campaigns according to the new architecture in the test account</li>
<li>Keep the original account running stably</li>
<li>Budget controlled at 20-30% of the original account</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Phase 2: Small-Scale Validation</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Run for 2-4 weeks to collect sufficient data</li>
<li>Compare efficiency metrics between old and new architectures</li>
<li>Identify details needing adjustment</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Phase 3: Gradual Migration</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Gradually migrate budget from old account to new account</li>
<li>Observe data stability weekly</li>
<li>Prepare rollback plan</li>
</ul>
<h3>7.3 Continuous Optimization and Iteration</h3>
<p><strong>Refined architecture is not a one-time project</strong>, it requires continuous optimization:</p>
<p><strong>Weekly Checks</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Is each Ad Set's sample size sufficient?</li>
<li>Are there signs of fatigue (frequency too high)?</li>
<li>Are there abnormal fluctuations in CTR/CVR?</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Monthly Evaluation</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Which Ad Sets need scaling?</li>
<li>Which Ad Sets need to be paused?</li>
<li>Are there new testing opportunities?</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Quarterly Review</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Does the overall architecture need adjustment?</li>
<li>Do competitor and market changes require response?</li>
<li>Are new platform features worth testing?</li>
</ul>
<h2>Part 8: Common Problems and Solutions</h2>
<h3>8.1 Audience Overlap Problem</h3>
<p><strong>Problem</strong>: Multiple Ad Sets have highly overlapping audiences, causing internal competition and cost increases.</p>
<p><strong>Solution</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Use Meta's "Audience Overlap" diagnostic tool</li>
<li>Consider merging Ad Sets with overlap rates exceeding 20%</li>
<li>Use Audience Network or Placement adjustments to avoid overlap</li>
<li>Split by region or device to reduce overlap</li>
</ul>
<h3>8.2 Data Sparsity Problem</h3>
<p><strong>Problem</strong>: Over-segmentation leads to insufficient sample size for individual Ad Sets, making it impossible to draw statistically significant conclusions.</p>
<p><strong>Solution</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Set minimum sample size standards (e.g., at least 50 conversions per day for each Ad Set)</li>
<li>Use platform smart bidding (e.g., Meta's Advantage+) to supplement data</li>
<li>Adjust segmentation dimensions and use broader audience definitions</li>
<li>Extend testing periods to accumulate data</li>
</ul>
<h3>8.3 Difficulty Scaling</h3>
<p><strong>Problem</strong>: Small-scale testing is effective, but performance drops sharply when scaled up.</p>
<p><strong>Solution</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Check if you're reaching "easy-to-convert users" (e.g., users with existing brand awareness)</li>
<li>When expanding Lookalike Audiences, use broader ratios (from 1% to 2-3%)</li>
<li>Coordinate with creative fatigue management, continuously add new materials</li>
<li>Consider entering new markets or platforms to find incremental growth</li>
</ul>
<h2>Part 9: Conclusion</h2>
<p><strong>Refined account structure is a systematic project to improve overseas advertising efficiency</strong>, which requires:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Clear Hierarchical Logic</strong>: Each level bears clear responsibilities</li>
<li><strong>Scientific Test Design</strong>: Follow the single variable principle</li>
<li><strong>Continuous Iteration Optimization</strong>: Data-driven decision-making, rapid hypothesis testing</li>
<li><strong>Reasonable Naming Management</strong>: Easy identification and analysis</li>
<li><strong>Flexible Scalable Design</strong>: Support business growth needs</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Core Action Checklist</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>☐ Audit existing account structure, identify problem areas</li>
<li>☐ Develop new naming conventions and structural standards</li>
<li>☐ Validate new architecture in test account</li>
<li>☐ Establish daily monitoring and weekly optimization mechanisms</li>
<li>☐ Continuously record learnings, accumulate best practices</li>
</ul>
<p>Mastering the construction methods of refined account structure will lay a solid efficiency foundation for your overseas advertising. Remember: <strong>Good architecture makes an optimizer's work twice as effective with half the effort, while poor architecture makes all optimization efforts twice as difficult with half the results</strong>.</p>
